# anti-patterns.mdc

## Forbidden Planning Behaviors

* Never create documentation trees without execution value
* Never create folder forests for visual organization
* Never mistake more folders for better planning
* Never generate template-driven fake structure
* Never create files that do not directly support execution
* Never preserve conflicting legacy behavior when architecture laws change

## Forbidden Version Behaviors

* Never guess missing versions
* Never silently infer release targets
* Never merge release scopes casually
* Never create plan versions without explicit release mapping
* Never allow release-vX and plan-vX to drift apart
* Never write release changelog history outside /.forge/releases/changelog.json
* Never overwrite historical changelog entries

## Forbidden Execution Behaviors

* Never leave deterministic `/plan` or doc tooling logic only as throwaway terminal snippets when it should live under `/.forge/scripts/` (see `forge-scripts.mdc`)
* Never run repo Python with system interpreters or global pip when `.venv` exists or must exist (use `.venv` only)
* Never optimize for visible progress over validated progress
* Never mark work complete without proof
* Never skip rollback definition
* Never allow dependency-unsafe execution
* Never allow hidden regressions for convenience
* Never allow planning before release synthesis

## Forbidden Architecture Behaviors

* Never bypass architecture boundaries for speed
* Never introduce hidden coupling
* Never perform silent architectural changes
* Never replace correctness with convenience abstractions
* Never create complexity that increases navigation cost
* Never plan from requirements or tmp directly

## Examples

Bad:

architecture/system_design/
contracts/security_contracts/
execution/build_order/

Good:

architecture/SYSTEM_DESIGN.md
contracts/SECURITY_CONTRACTS.md
execution/BUILD_ORDER.md

## Final Rule

Operational truth over documentation aesthetics.

Execution clarity over visual structure.

Proof over optimism.

Always.
